was craving a carrot cake but i couldn’t find any on swiggy 🤓 so here it is

2 cups grated carrots (fresh, not the bagged stuff)
1 ½ cups flour (all-purpose works)
1 tsp baking soda
½ tsp baking powder
½ tsp salt
1 ½ tsp cinnamon
½ tsp nutmeg
½ cup oil (something neutral like canola or sunflower)
¾ cup brown sugar (or jaggery if you’re feeling healthy-ish)
2 eggs
1 tsp vanilla
optional: handful of walnuts or raisins or both

mix dry stuff in one bowl.
wet stuff in another.
combine, fold in carrots, then walnuts or raisins if you want.
pour into a greased tin.
bake at 180°C (350°F) for about 30-35 mins.

let it cool (seriously, don’t rush it).

wait for part II as i show the frosting xx

We started Day Two at Siddhatek, where Ganesha is worshipped as Siddhivinayak, the giver of siddhi spiritual power and determination. The temple sits quietly by the river, and there’s something about the stillness that makes you look inward. Here, people prayed for discipline the kind that helps you keep going even when motivation disappears.

Next was Mahaganpati at Ranjangaon, where Ganesha is known in his most powerful form. The temple felt grand, but not overwhelming. It was a reminder that true strength isn’t loud it’s steady. We prayed for courage, not to fight battles outside, but to face the ones within our doubts, fears, and limits.

By this time reading the story behind each ganpati felt so much more meaningful and nurturing to what i know gannu bappa as, it felt so grand and more believable as an entity. 
By afternoon, we reached Vighneshwar at Ozar, the remover of obstacles. It was calm, almost comforting, like the feeling of everything slowly falling into place. We prayed for ease not for life to be easy, but for grace in the hard parts, atleast thats what mom told me to think of in a way. For the wisdom to know when to push forward and when to let go.

And finally, we climbed to Lenyadri, where Ganesha is worshipped as Girijatmaj, the son of Parvati. The temple is carved into a mountain, and the climb feels like a metaphor step by step, breath by breath. At the top, the view stretched wide and open, like your thoughts after a long exhale. Here, we prayed for growth not just upward, but inward. Ofcourse the monkeys prayed with us

Day 2, Four temples. One climb. A day that taught us power doesn’t always look like force. it can feel like patience, clarity, and quiet faith.

Started our Ganesha yatra from Lonavala at 11 AM, and somehow managed to cover four temples in a day each one with its own meaning, its own energy. ✨

We began at Ballaleshwar, Pali, where Ganesha is known for standing by his true devotees. Here, we prayed for faith to believe in ourselves and our path, even when things feel uncertain.

Next was Varadvinayak, Mahad the giver of boons. This temple felt warm and welcoming, like a reminder that good things come when you’re open to receiving. We prayed for opportunities and support in all forms.

By afternoon, we reached Chintamani, Theur, where Ganesha is said to remove worries. It was peaceful, almost meditative. We prayed for mental clarity, to stop overthinking and just breathe.

We ended the day at Mayureshwar, Morgaon, where Ganesha symbolizes victory over ego and fear. Under the night sky, it felt powerful. We asked for inner strength the kind that helps you stay grounded no matter what life throws at you.

Four temples. Twelve hours. A day full of quiet realizations and steady prayers.

So we decided to check out this underground cave in Hatta, UAE. Now, technically, caves like this shouldn’t even exist here since it’s a desert, but somehow we found one! We paid around 100 AED (don’t quite remember if it was 100 or 90), and to be honest, for that price, I expected a bit more of a “Khatron Ke Khiladi” kind of vibe. Imagine more bats, more rats basically, make it scarier, right? 🤠 But, okay, I was still terrified because I get super claustrophobic in closed spaces, and that cave felt like a constant fight for air.
It’s about a 45-minute walk inside, navigating rocks and flowing water, with some parts getting so narrow you wonder if you’re gonna make it out! There were bats, though, which definitely added a bit of drama. All in all, not exactly what I expected, but a fun experience. I’ll give it an 8/10, mainly for the masti points
